<subSubSection id="88CE52A93757B000FF02FAEEFD9A64A7" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="502" pageId="2" pageNumber="501" type="description">
<paragraph id="C06B01223757B001FF02FAEEFECE62AD" blockId="2.[178,1085,1364,1473]" pageId="2" pageNumber="501">
Redescription: Body length 9.0-10.0 mm; length of forebody 
<quantity id="072CACC73757B001FC0CFAEEFBBD6205" box="[956,1081,1364,1386]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.449999999999999" metricValueMax="5.8" metricValueMin="5.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="501" unit="mm" value="5.449999999999999" valueMax="5.8" valueMin="5.1">5.1-5.8 mm</quantity>
. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73757B001FEF1FACBFEFB62EB" box="[321,383,1393,1415]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="501">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
. Coloration: body blackish-brown; legs yellowish-brown to reddish, with the profemora and protibiae occasionally somewhat darker brown; antennae brown to dark-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06B01223757B001FF02FA75FE646156" blockId="2.[178,1085,1487,1594]" pageId="2" pageNumber="501">
Head (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73757B001FF48FA75FEB36289" box="[248,311,1487,1509]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="501">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) approximately as broad as long, broadest across eyes, convexly tapering posteriad behind eyes; punctation (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73757B001FDAEFA56FDD9616E" box="[542,605,1516,1538]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="501">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
) rather coarse, distinctly umbilicate, and very dense, interstices forming narrow ridges. Antenna 3.8-4.0 mm long; antennomere X nearly twice as long as broad.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06B01223756B000FF02FF60FDF8662F" blockId="3.[178,1085,217,323]" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73756B000FE97FF63FEE36783" box="[295,359,217,239]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) short, 1.13 times as long as broad and 0.97-0.98 times as broad as head, widest at anterior angles and distinctly tapering posteriad; lateral margins convex in dorsal view; punctation (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73756B000FE7EFEABFD89664B" box="[462,525,273,295]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
) similar to that of head; midline with or without rudiment of narrow glossy band in posterior half.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06B01223756B000FF02FEEBFD9E66BB" blockId="3.[178,1085,337,471]" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">
Elytra (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73756B000FF4FFEEBFEB8660B" box="[255,316,337,359]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
) approximately 0.8 times as long as pronotum, each elytron with indistinct three irregular longitudinal, narrowly elevated ridges; suture weakly elevated; macropunctation coarse and partly somewhat seriate (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73756B000FD10FE33FD6466F3" box="[672,736,393,415]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
); interstices with irregular micropunctation, otherwise not microsculptured. Hind wings apparently reduced. Protarsomeres I-IV rather weakly dilated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06B01223756B000FF02FE5CFEA8651E" blockId="3.[178,1085,486,626]" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Abdomen nearly as broad as elytra; anterior impressions of tergites III-VI not very coarsely sculptured; punctation extremely fine and extremely dense on tergites III-VII, even finer, but slightly less dense on tergite VIII; interstices with distinct microreticulation; posterior margin of tergite VII with palisade fringe; tergite VIII with convex posterior margin.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06B01223756B000FF77FD38FB80642A" blockId="3.[178,1085,641,838]" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">
: tergite VIII with weakly convex posterior margin; sternite VII (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73756B000FC30FD3BFC4565FB" box="[896,961,641,663]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) with short unmodified pubescence, posterior margin broadly concave; sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73756B000FC0DFD24FC7A65D8" box="[957,1022,670,692]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) with shallow median depression, this depression with unmodified pubescence, on either side of the posterior excision with cluster of short dark setae; aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73756B000FCD0FD63FC196583" box="[864,925,729,751]" captionStart="Figs 1-8" captionStartId="4.[178,218,1512,1532]" captionTargetBox="[179,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetId="figure-2@4.[178,1082,212,1493]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figs 1-8: Domene scabripennis ROUGEMONT (paratype): (1) habitus; (2) forebody; (3) median dorsal portion of head; (4) median portion of pronotum; (5) sutural portion of elytra; (6) male sternite VII; (7) male sternite VIII; (8) aedeagus in lateral view. Scale bars: 1-2: 1.0 mm; 6-8: 0.5 mm; 3-5: 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305259" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305259/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
) approximately 
<quantity id="072CACC73756B000FF02FD4CFE8B6460" box="[178,271,758,780]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" pageId="3" pageNumber="502" unit="mm" value="1.15">1.15 mm</quantity>
long; ventral process very slender and weakly curved in lateral view; dorsal plate lamellate and moderately sclerotized, with long apical and very short, weakly sclerotized basal portion; internal sac with pair of hook-shaped sclerotized sclerites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C06B01223756B000FF77FCE5FD9A64A7" blockId="3.[178,1086,862,972]" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">: tergite VIII with truncate posterior margin; sternite VIII weakly transverse, posterior margin convex, in the middle weakly concave; tergite IX undivided in the middle and with short postero-lateral processes; tergite X of ovoid shape, distinctly longer than antero-median portion of tergite IX.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="88CE52A93756B000FF02FC59FE0B6302" pageId="3" pageNumber="502" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C06B01223756B000FF02FC59FE0B6302" blockId="3.[178,1085,995,1134]" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">
Comparative notes: This species is distinguished from other representatives of the 
<taxonomicName id="07D47AA13756B000FE9AFBBBFE4F637A" authorityName="Assing &amp; Feldmann" authorityYear="2014" box="[298,459,1024,1046]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Domene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scabripennis">
<emphasis id="F2A0DD303756B000FE9AFBBBFE4F637A" box="[298,459,1024,1046]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">D. scabripennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, by the shape and chaetotaxy of the male sternite VIII, as well as by the shape of the ventral process of the aedeagus. For details regarding characters separating it from 
<taxonomicName id="07D47AA13756B000FE6AFB86FDCB633D" authorityName="Assing &amp; Feldmann" authorityYear="2014" box="[474,591,1083,1105]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Domene" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="502" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alesiana">
<emphasis id="F2A0DD303756B000FE6AFB86FDCB633D" box="[474,591,1083,1105]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">D. alesiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, its closest relative, see the comparative notes in the following section.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="88CE52A93756B000FF02FBC4FE1462AB" pageId="3" pageNumber="502" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="C06B01223756B000FF02FBC4FE1462AB" blockId="3.[178,1086,1150,1480]" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">
Distribution: The known distribution is confined to the Anmashan, 
<collectingRegion id="0210CFC03756B000FC6DFBC4FBB963F8" box="[989,1085,1150,1172]" country="Taiwan" name="Taichung" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Taichung</collectingRegion>
Hsien, 
<collectingCountry id="B8C341B23756B000FF4BFB27FEC363DF" box="[251,327,1181,1203]" name="Taiwan" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Taiwan</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="58EF1DA73756B000FEE5FB27FE1C63DF" box="[341,408,1181,1203]" captionStart="Map 1" captionStartId="2.[178,223,876,896]" captionTargetBox="[178,1083,212,857]" captionTargetId="figure-2@2.[178,1083,212,858]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Map 1: Distributions of the species of the Domene scabripennis group: D. immarginata (white circles), D. sagittata (black diamond), D. scabripennis (black triangle), D. alesiana (white triangle), and D. firmicornis (black circle)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5305257" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5305257/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">Map 1</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="1F6FBF803756B000FE6DFB24FD8D63DF" box="[477,521,1182,1203]" pageId="3" pageNumber="502">type</typeStatus>
specimens were collected with pitfall traps baited with chicken droppings in a broadleaved evergreen forest. The additional material was partly collected with yellow pan traps set in a primary mixed forest with numerous large dead trees and a lot of dead wood on the forest floor [T122] and in an old broadleaved forest [T124]. The remaining specimens were sifted from leaf litter, rotting twigs, and other debris around trunks of large dead trees in an old broadleaved forest [T127], from leaf litter and fermenting covers of tree buds accumulated along a forest road after heavy rains [T129], and from leaf litter, various debris, and rotting wood in a mature mixed forest with numerous old dead trees [T130] (SMETANA pers. comm.). The altitudes range from 
<quantity id="072CACC73756B000FF59FA08FE0F62AB" box="[233,395,1458,1480]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.19" metricValueMax="2.23" metricValueMin="2.15" pageId="3" pageNumber="502" unit="m" value="2190.0" valueMax="2230.0" valueMin="2150.0">2150 to 2230 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
